    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "A marketing company needs to analyze customer reviews of their products in reverse order to see how customer sentiment has evolved over time.\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #1:** In the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">Marketing</code> class, write the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">reverseReviews()</code> method to modify the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">reviews</code> list so that the reviews appear in reverse order.\r\n\r\n- Use a loop to swap elements from the beginning and end of the list.\r\n- Modify the original reviews list instead of creating a new one.\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO #2:** In the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">MarketingRunner</code> class:\r\n\r\n- Call the <code>reverseReviews()</code> method.\r\n- Print the reversed reviews using the <code>resultsToString()</code> method.\r\n\r\n<details style=\"background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;\">\r\n    <summary style=\"font-size: 1.2em; font-weight: bold;\">🔦 Need help with your algorithm?</summary>\r\n    <div style=\"margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;\">\r\n    \t<p>Here is one approach to solving this problem.</p>\r\n        <pre style=\"background-color: #333333; color: white;\">\r\nset back to the last index of reviews\r\n&nbsp;\r\nLoop from front = 0 to front < (size of reviews) / 2\r\n  create a new temp variable and set to the review at front\r\n  set the review at index front to the review at index back\r\n  set the review at index back to the review at temp\r\n  move front forward (in the loop header)\r\n  move back backward\r\n</pre>\r\n    </div>\r\n</details>",
